### 1. One-Line Summary
Tenergy 05 is the benchmark for high-arc, heavy-spin looping with a very high performance ceiling, but it is more sensitive and demanding in the short game. Yasaka Rakza 7 offers a more linear, controlled ESN-style response thats easier to access and manage across a wider range of players, with slightly less top-end bite than Tenergy 05.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * Tenergy 05: Bouncy and lively even with compact strokes; the ball comes off earlier and can jump long if touch is not clean.
        * Rakza 7: More contained at low power; easier to keep short and place accurately without the ball popping up.
    * **Top End:**
        * Tenergy 05: Higher peak speed when you fully engage the sponge; excellent finishing power after the loop lands.
        * Rakza 7: Strong top end for its class, but the last gear is lower; feels less explosive at full swing.
    * **Linearity:**
        * Tenergy 05: More springy and gear-dependent; rewards acceleration but can feel non-linear between soft and hard impacts.
        * Rakza 7: Noticeably more linear and predictable; power scales more proportionally with swing speed.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * Tenergy 05: Elite for opening vs backspin—high throw plus strong grab makes heavy, safe first loops.
        * Rakza 7: Very good opener, but needs a bit more forward engagement to match Tenergy 05s easy arc and bite.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * Tenergy 05: Higher spin ceiling on full brush and fast acceleration; produces heavier kick after the bounce.
        * Rakza 7: High spin for ESN, but the absolute peak is a step below; easier to access near-max spin consistently.
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * Tenergy 05: Extremely effective grip under speed; excels in fast topspin rallies and counter-topspin.
        * Rakza 7: Grippy and reliable, slightly less locked-in at very high rpm/speed compared with Tenergy 05.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * Tenergy 05: Higher arc (classic high throw); naturally clears the net with topspin safety.
        * Rakza 7: Medium-high arc; flatter than Tenergy 05, giving a more direct trajectory.
    * **Safety:**
        * Tenergy 05: Very safe for looping if you commit to topspin; less forgiving if you try to hold back with passive contact.
        * Rakza 7: Safer for controlled placements and mixed tempos; easier when you need to take pace off.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * Tenergy 05: Crisp, springy catapult feel; impact can feel sharper and more reactive.
        * Rakza 7: More traditional ESN feel—slightly softer and more buffered; clearer sense of how much youre engaging.
    * **Dwell:**
        * Tenergy 05: Good dwell at high brush/acceleration, but quick rebound on passive touch.
        * Rakza 7: Slightly longer, more controllable dwell at medium impacts; helps stabilize roll-y loops and controlled topspin.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * Tenergy 05: More sensitive to incoming spin; reads serve/receive quality strongly—great when your touch is sharp, punishing when it isnt.
        * Rakza 7: Less spin-reactive; easier to keep receive simple and stable, especially on banana flick setups and short pushes.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * Tenergy 05: Requires very clean hands to keep short; bounciness demands precise racket angle and relaxed grip.
        * Rakza 7: Easier to drop short, push tight, and vary depth; more forgiving for stop shots and soft blocks.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * Tenergy 05: Can be fast and stable if angle is correct, but the spring can send the ball long under heavy topspin.
        * Rakza 7: More controlled passive block; ball stays on the table with fewer surprises.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * Tenergy 05: Outstanding counter-topspin—high grip and arc help you bite through incoming spin.
        * Rakza 7: Very solid countering with a more direct line; slightly less vicious at the top end but easier to time.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Tenergy 05 if:**
    * You win points with first-ball attack: heavy opening loops vs backspin and high-arc topspin pressure.
    * You play close-to-mid distance with frequent counter-topspin and want maximum spin kick.
    * Your serve/receive and touch game are already clean enough to manage a bouncy, spin-sensitive rubber.
* **Choose Rakza 7 if:**
    * You want an all-around offensive rubber that loops well but stays predictable in control phases.
    * You value easier serve/receive, short pushes, and placement-based play without losing topspin quality.
    * You prefer a more linear response for consistent timing, especially under pressure or in mixed-tempo rallies.
